# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chemical-equilibrium
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] In a chemical reaction, **chemical equilibrium** is the state in which both the reactants and products are present in concentrations which have no further tendency to change with time, so that there is no observable change in the properties of the system.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] This state results when the forward reaction proceeds at the same rate as the reverse reaction.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The reaction rates of the forward and backward reactions are generally not zero, but they are equal.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Thus, there are no net changes in the concentrations of the reactants and products.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Such a state is known as dynamic equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] It is the subject of study of *equilibrium chemistry*.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The concept of chemical equilibrium was developed in 1803, after Berthollet found that some chemical reactions are reversible.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] For any reaction mixture to exist at equilibrium, the rates of the forward and backward (reverse) reactions must be equal.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] In the following chemical equation, arrows point both ways to indicate equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The equilibrium concentration position of a reaction is said to lie "far to the right" if, at equilibrium, nearly all the reactants are consumed.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Conversely the equilibrium position is said to be "far to the left" if hardly any product is formed from the reactants.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] where A, B, S and T are active masses and *k*+ and *k*− are rate constants.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] and the ratio of the rate constants is also a constant, now known as an equilibrium constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] By convention, the products form the numerator.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Equality of forward and backward reaction rates, however, is a necessary condition for chemical equilibrium, though it is not sufficient to explain why equilibrium occurs.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Despite the limitations of this derivation, the equilibrium constant for a reaction is indeed a constant, independent of the activities of the various species involved, though it does depend on temperature as observed by the van 't Hoff equation.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Adding a catalyst will affect both the forward reaction and the reverse reaction in the same way and will not have an effect on the equilibrium constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The catalyst will speed up both reactions thereby increasing the speed at which equilibrium is reached.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Although the macroscopic equilibrium concentrations are constant in time, reactions do occur at the molecular level.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] a proton may hop from one molecule of acetic acid onto a water molecule and then onto an acetate anion to form another molecule of acetic acid and leaving the number of acetic acid molecules unchanged.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] This is an example of dynamic equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Equilibria, like the rest of thermodynamics, are statistical phenomena, averages of microscopic behavior.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] If mineral acid is added to the acetic acid mixture, increasing the concentration of hydronium ion, the amount of dissociation must decrease as the reaction is driven to the left in accordance with this principle.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] If {H3O+} increases {CH3CO2H} must increase and CH3CO−2 must decrease.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The H2O is left out, as it is the solvent and its concentration remains high and nearly constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Gibbs suggested in 1873 that equilibrium is attained when the "available energy" (now known as Gibbs free energy or Gibbs energy) of the system is at its minimum value, assuming the reaction is carried out at a constant temperature and pressure.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] What this means is that the derivative of the Gibbs energy with respect to reaction coordinate (a measure of the extent of reaction that has occurred, ranging from zero for all reactants to a maximum for all products) vanishes (because dG = 0), signaling a stationary point.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] This derivative is called the reaction Gibbs energy (or energy change) and corresponds to the difference between the chemical potentials of reactants and products at the composition of the reaction mixture.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] This criterion is both necessary and sufficient.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] If a mixture is not at equilibrium, the liberation of the excess Gibbs energy (or Helmholtz energy at constant volume reactions) is the "driving force" for the composition of the mixture to change until equilibrium is reached.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] where *R* is the universal gas constant and *T* the temperature (In Kelvin).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] When the reactants are dissolved in a medium of high ionic strength the quotient of activity coefficients may be taken to be constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] where [A] is the concentration of A, etc., is independent of the analytical concentration of the reactants.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] For this reason, equilibrium constants for solutions are usually determined in media of high ionic strength.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] *Kc* varies with ionic strength, temperature and pressure (or volume).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Likewise *Kp* for gases depends on partial pressure.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] These constants are easier to measure and encountered in high-school chemistry courses.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] At constant temperature and pressure, one must consider the Gibbs free energy, *G*, while at constant temperature and volume, one must consider the Helmholtz free energy, *A*, for the reaction; and at constant internal energy and volume, one must consider the entropy, *S*, for the reaction.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The constant volume case is important in geochemistry and atmospheric chemistry where pressure variations are significant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Note that, if reactants and products were in standard state (completely pure), then there would be no reversibility and no equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Indeed, they would necessarily occupy disjoint volumes of space.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The mixing of the products and reactants contributes a large entropy increase (known as entropy of mixing) to states containing equal mixture of products and reactants and gives rise to a distinctive minimum in the Gibbs energy as a function of the extent of reaction.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The standard Gibbs energy change, together with the Gibbs energy of mixing, determine the equilibrium state.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] In this article only the **constant pressure** case is considered.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The relation between the Gibbs free energy and the equilibrium constant can be found by considering chemical potentials.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] At constant temperature and pressure in the absence of an applied voltage, the Gibbs free energy, *G*, for the reaction depends only on the extent of reaction: *ξ* (Greek letter xi), and can only decrease according to the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] It means that the derivative of *G* with respect to *ξ* must be negative if the reaction happens; at the equilibrium this derivative is equal to zero.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] In order to meet the thermodynamic condition for equilibrium, the Gibbs energy must be stationary, meaning that the derivative of *G* with respect to the extent of reaction, *ξ*, must be zero.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] It can be shown that in this case, the sum of chemical potentials times the stoichiometric coefficients of the products is equal to the sum of those corresponding to the reactants.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Therefore, the sum of the Gibbs energies of the reactants must be the equal to the sum of the Gibbs energies of the products.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] where *μ* is in this case a partial molar Gibbs energy, a chemical potential.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The chemical potential of a reagent A is a function of the activity, {A} of that reagent.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] (where *μ*o A is the **standard chemical potential**).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Inserting *dNi* = *νi dξ* into the above equation gives a stoichiometric coefficient ( $\nu _{i}~$ ) and a differential that denotes the reaction occurring to an infinitesimal extent (*dξ*).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] which is the Gibbs free energy change for the reaction.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] which is the **standard Gibbs energy change for the reaction** that can be calculated using thermodynamical tables.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Obtaining the value of the standard Gibbs energy change, allows the calculation of the equilibrium constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] For a reactional system at equilibrium: *Q*r = *K*eq; *ξ* = *ξ*eq.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] In simplifications where the change in reaction quotient is solely due to the concentration changes, *Q*r is referred to as the mass-action ratio, and the ratio *Q*r/*K*eq is referred to as the disequilibrium ratio.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Note that activities and equilibrium constants are dimensionless numbers.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The expression for the equilibrium constant can be rewritten as the product of a concentration quotient, *K*c and an activity coefficient quotient, *Γ*.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] [A] is the concentration of reagent A, etc.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] It is possible in principle to obtain values of the activity coefficients, γ.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] For solutions, equations such as the Debye–Hückel equation or extensions such as Davies equation Specific ion interaction theory or Pitzer equations may be used.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] It is common practice to assume that *Γ* is a constant, and to use the concentration quotient in place of the thermodynamic equilibrium constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] It is also general practice to use the term *equilibrium constant* instead of the more accurate *concentration quotient*.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] For reactions in the gas phase partial pressure is used in place of concentration and fugacity coefficient in place of activity coefficient.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] In the real world, for example, when making ammonia in industry, fugacity coefficients must be taken into account.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Fugacity, *f*, is the product of partial pressure and fugacity coefficient.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] so the general expression defining an equilibrium constant is valid for both solution and gas phases.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] In aqueous solution, equilibrium constants are usually determined in the presence of an "inert" electrolyte such as sodium nitrate, NaNO3, or potassium perchlorate, KClO4.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] where *ci* and *zi* stand for the concentration and ionic charge of ion type *i*, and the sum is taken over all the *N* types of charged species in solution.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] When the concentration of dissolved salt is much higher than the analytical concentrations of the reagents, the ions originating from the dissolved salt determine the ionic strength, and the ionic strength is effectively constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Since activity coefficients depend on ionic strength, the activity coefficients of the species are effectively independent of concentration.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Thus, the assumption that *Γ* is constant is justified.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The concentration quotient is a simple multiple of the equilibrium constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] However, *K*c will vary with ionic strength.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] If it is measured at a series of different ionic strengths, the value can be extrapolated to zero ionic strength.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The concentration quotient obtained in this manner is known, paradoxically, as a thermodynamic equilibrium constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Before using a published value of an equilibrium constant in conditions of ionic strength different from the conditions used in its determination, the value should be adjusted.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] A mixture may appear to have no tendency to change, though it is not at equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] For example, a mixture of SO2 and O2 is metastable as there is a kinetic barrier to formation of the product, SO3.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The barrier can be overcome when a catalyst is also present in the mixture as in the contact process, but the catalyst does not affect the equilibrium concentrations.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] but almost instantaneous in the presence of the catalytic enzyme carbonic anhydrase.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] When pure substances (liquids or solids) are involved in equilibria their activities do not appear in the equilibrium constant because their numerical values are considered one.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] For all but very concentrated solutions, the water can be considered a "pure" liquid, and therefore it has an activity of one.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] It is perfectly legitimate to write [H+] for the hydronium ion concentration, since the state of solvation of the proton is constant (in dilute solutions) and so does not affect the equilibrium concentrations.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] *K*w varies with variation in ionic strength and/or temperature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The concentrations of H+ and OH− are not independent quantities.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Most commonly [OH−] is replaced by *K*w[H+]−1 in equilibrium constant expressions which would otherwise include hydroxide ion.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Solids also do not appear in the equilibrium constant expression, if they are considered to be pure and thus their activities taken to be one.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Consider the case of a dibasic acid H2A.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] When dissolved in water, the mixture will contain H2A, HA− and A2−.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] This equilibrium can be split into two steps in each of which one proton is liberated.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Note that these constants are dissociation constants because the products on the right hand side of the equilibrium expression are dissociation products.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] In many systems, it is preferable to use association constants.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Thus, for exothermic reactions (Δ*H* is negative), *K* decreases with an increase in temperature, but, for endothermic reactions, (Δ*H* is positive) *K* increases with an increase in temperature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] At first sight this appears to offer a means of obtaining the standard molar enthalpy of the reaction by studying the variation of *K* with temperature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] In practice, however, the method is unreliable because error propagation almost always gives very large errors on the values calculated in this way.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The effect of electric field on equilibrium has been studied by Manfred Eigen among others.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Equilibrium can be broadly classified as heterogeneous and homogeneous equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Homogeneous equilibrium consists of reactants and products belonging in the same phase whereas heterogeneous equilibrium comes into play for reactants and products in different phases.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] In these applications, terms such as stability constant, formation constant, binding constant, affinity constant, association constant and dissociation constant are used.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] In biochemistry, it is common to give units for binding constants, which serve to define the concentration units used when the constant's value was determined.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] When the only equilibrium is that of the formation of a 1:1 adduct as the composition of a mixture, there are many ways that the composition of a mixture can be calculated.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] For example, see ICE table for a traditional method of calculating the pH of a solution of a weak acid.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] There are three approaches to the general calculation of the composition of a mixture at equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Minimize the Gibbs energy of the system.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The equations of mass balance are simply statements that demonstrate that the total concentration of each reactant must be constant by the law of conservation of mass.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] In general, the calculations are rather complicated or complex.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] For instance, in the case of a dibasic acid, H2A dissolved in water the two reactants can be specified as the conjugate base, A2−, and the proton, H+.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] with TA the total concentration of species A.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Note that it is customary to omit the ionic charges when writing and using these equations.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] When the equilibrium constants are known and the total concentrations are specified there are two equations in two unknown "free concentrations" [A] and [H].
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] so the concentrations of the "complexes" are calculated from the free concentrations and the equilibrium constants.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] It is easy to see how this can be extended to three or more reagents.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The composition of solutions containing reactants A and H is easy to calculate as a function of p[H].
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] When [H] is known, the free concentration [A] is calculated from the mass-balance equation in A.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The diagram alongside, shows an example of the hydrolysis of the aluminium Lewis acid Al3+(aq) shows the species concentrations for a 5 × 10−6 M solution of an aluminium salt as a function of pH.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Each concentration is shown as a percentage of the total aluminium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] The diagram above illustrates the point that a precipitate that is not one of the main species in the solution equilibrium may be formed.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] At pH just below 5.5 the main species present in a 5 μM solution of Al3+ are aluminium hydroxides Al(OH)2+, AlOH+2 and Al13(OH)7+32, but on raising the pH Al(OH)3 precipitates from the solution.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] This occurs because Al(OH)3 has a very large lattice energy.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] As the pH rises more and more Al(OH)3 comes out of solution.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] This is an example of Le Châtelier's principle in action: Increasing the concentration of the hydroxide ion causes more aluminium hydroxide to precipitate, which removes hydroxide from the solution.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] When the hydroxide concentration becomes sufficiently high the soluble aluminate, Al(OH)−4, is formed.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] Another common instance where precipitation occurs is when a metal cation interacts with an anionic ligand to form an electrically neutral complex.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] If the complex is hydrophobic, it will precipitate out of water.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/chemical-equilibrium] This occurs with the nickel ion Ni2+ and dimethylglyoxime, (dmgH2): in this case the lattice energy of the solid is not particularly large, but it greatly exceeds the energy of solvation of the molecule Ni(dmgH)2.
