[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] In chemistry, the **common-ion effect** refers to the decrease in solubility of an ionic precipitate by the addition to the solution of a soluble compound with an ion in common with the precipitate.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] This behaviour is a consequence of Le Chatelier's principle for the equilibrium reaction of the ionic association/dissociation.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] The effect is commonly seen as an effect on the solubility of salts and other weak electrolytes.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] Adding an additional amount of one of the ions of the salt generally leads to increased precipitation of the salt, which reduces the concentration of both ions of the salt until the solubility equilibrium is reached.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] The effect is based on the fact that both the original salt and the other added chemical have one ion in common with each other.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] Hydrogen sulfide (H2S) is a weak electrolyte.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] If HCl is added to the H2S solution, H+ is a common ion and creates a common ion effect.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] Due to the increase in concentration of H+ ions from the added HCl, the equilibrium of the dissociation of H2S shifts to the left and keeps the value of Ka constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] Thus the dissociation of H2S decreases, the concentration of un-ionized H2S increases, and as a result, the concentration of sulfide ions decreases.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] Its solubility in pure water is 7.32 × 10−4 M.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] However in a solution that is 0.0200 M in barium nitrate, Ba(NO3)2, the increase in the common ion barium leads to a decrease in iodate ion concentration.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] The solubility is therefore reduced to 1.40 × 10−4 M, about five times smaller.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] A practical example used very widely in areas drawing drinking water from chalk or limestone aquifers is the addition of sodium carbonate to the raw water to reduce the hardness of the water.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] In the water treatment process, highly soluble sodium carbonate salt is added to precipitate out sparingly soluble calcium carbonate.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] The very pure and finely divided precipitate of calcium carbonate that is generated is a valuable by-product used in the manufacture of toothpaste.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] The salting-out process used in the manufacture of soaps benefits from the common-ion effect.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] Addition of sodium chloride reduces the solubility of the soap salts.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] The soaps precipitate due to a combination of common-ion effect and increased ionic strength.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] Sea, brackish and other waters that contain appreciable amount of sodium ions (Na+) interfere with the normal behavior of soap because of common-ion effect.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] In the presence of excess Na+, the solubility of soap salts is reduced, making the soap less effective.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] A buffer solution contains an acid and its conjugate base or a base and its conjugate acid.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] Addition of the conjugate ion will result in a change of pH of the buffer solution.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] For example, if both sodium acetate and acetic acid are dissolved in the same solution they both dissociate and ionize to produce acetate ions.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] Sodium acetate is a strong electrolyte, so it dissociates completely in solution.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] Acetic acid is a weak acid, so it only ionizes slightly.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] According to Le Chatelier's principle, the addition of acetate ions from sodium acetate will suppress the ionization of acetic acid and shift its equilibrium to the left.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] Thus the percent dissociation of the acetic acid will decrease, and the pH of the solution will increase.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] The ionization of an acid or a base is limited by the presence of its conjugate base or acid.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] This will decrease the hydronium concentration, and thus the common-ion solution will be less acidic than a solution containing only acetic acid.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] Many transition-metal compounds violate this rule due to the formation of complex ions, a scenario not part of the equilibria that are involved in simple precipitation of salts from ionic solution.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] For example, copper(I) chloride is insoluble in water, but it dissolves when chloride ions are added, such as when hydrochloric acid is added.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] This is due to the formation of soluble CuCl2− complex ions.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] Sometimes adding an ion other than the ones that are part of the precipitated salt itself can increase the solubility of the salt.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] This "salting in" is called the "uncommon-ion effect" (also "salt effect" or the "diverse-ion effect").
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] It occurs because as the total ion concentration increases, inter-ion attraction within the solution can become an important factor.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/common-ion-effect] This alternate equilibrium makes the ions less available for the precipitation reaction.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The **equilibrium constant** of a chemical reaction is the value of its reaction quotient at chemical equilibrium, a state approached by a dynamic chemical system after sufficient time has elapsed at which its composition has no measurable tendency towards further change.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] For a given set of reaction conditions, the equilibrium constant is independent of the initial analytical concentrations of the reactant and product species in the mixture.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Thus, given the initial composition of a system, known equilibrium constant values can be used to determine the composition of the system at equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] However, reaction parameters like temperature, solvent, and ionic strength may all affect the value of the equilibrium constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] A knowledge of equilibrium constants is essential for the understanding of many chemical systems, as well as the biochemical processes such as oxygen transport by hemoglobin in blood and acid–base homeostasis in the human body.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Stability constants, formation constants, binding constants, association constants and dissociation constants are all types of **equilibrium constants**.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] a thermodynamic equilibrium constant, denoted by $K^{\ominus }$ , is defined to be the value of the reaction quotient *Qt* when forward and reverse reactions occur at the same rate.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] At chemical equilibrium, the chemical composition of the mixture does not change with time, and the Gibbs free energy change $\Delta G$ for the reaction is zero.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] If the composition of a mixture at equilibrium is changed by addition of some reagent, a new equilibrium position will be reached, given enough time.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] where {X} denotes the thermodynamic activity of reagent X at equilibrium, [X] the numerical value of the corresponding concentration in moles per liter, and γ the corresponding activity coefficient.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] If X is a gas, instead of [X] the numerical value of the partial pressure $P_{X}$ in bar is used.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] If it can be assumed that the quotient of activity coefficients, $\Gamma$ , is constant over a range of experimental conditions, such as pH, then an equilibrium constant can be derived as a quotient of concentrations.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] where *R* is the universal gas constant, *T* is the absolute temperature (in kelvins), and ln is the natural logarithm.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] This expression implies that $K^{\ominus }$ must be a pure number and cannot have a dimension, since logarithms can only be taken of pure numbers. $K_{c}$ must also be a pure number.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] does have the dimension of concentration raised to some power (see § Dimensionality, below).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Such reaction quotients are often referred to, in the biochemical literature, as equilibrium constants.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] For an equilibrium mixture of gases, an equilibrium constant can be defined in terms of partial pressure or fugacity.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] A cumulative or overall constant, given the symbol *β*, is the constant for the formation of a complex from reagents.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] A cumulative constant can always be expressed as the product of stepwise constants.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] There is no agreed notation for stepwise constants, though a symbol such as *K*L ML is sometimes found in the literature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] It is best always to define each stability constant by reference to an equilibrium expression.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] A particular use of a stepwise constant is in the determination of stability constant values outside the normal range for a given method.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] For example, EDTA complexes of many metals are outside the range for the potentiometric method.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The stability constants for those complexes were determined by competition with a weaker ligand.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The formation constant of [Pd(CN)4]2− was determined by the competition method.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] In organic chemistry and biochemistry it is customary to use p*K*a values for acid dissociation equilibria.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] where *log* denotes a logarithm to base 10 or common logarithm, and *K*diss is a stepwise acid dissociation constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] For bases, the base association constant, p*K*b is used.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] For any given acid or base the two constants are related by p*K*a + p*K*b = p*K*w, so p*K*a can always be used in calculations.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] On the other hand, stability constants for metal complexes, and binding constants for host–guest complexes are generally expressed as association constants.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] it is customary to use association constants for both ML and HL.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Also, in generalized computer programs dealing with equilibrium constants it is general practice to use cumulative constants rather than stepwise constants and to omit ionic charges from equilibrium expressions.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] For example, if NTA, nitrilotriacetic acid, N(CH2CO2H)3 is designated as H3L and forms complexes ML and MHL with a metal ion M, the following expressions would apply for the dissociation constants.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Note how the subscripts define the stoichiometry of the equilibrium product.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] When two or more sites in an asymmetrical molecule may be involved in an equilibrium reaction there are more than one possible equilibrium constants.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] For example, the molecule L-DOPA has two non-equivalent hydroxyl groups which may be deprotonated.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Denoting L-DOPA as LH2, the following diagram shows all the species that may be formed (X = CH 2CH(NH 2)CO 2H).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The concentration of the species LH is equal to the sum of the concentrations of the two micro-species with the same chemical formula, labelled L1H and L2H.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The constant *K*2 is for a reaction with these two micro-species as products, so that [LH] = [L1H] + [L2H] appears in the numerator, and it follows that this **macro-constant** is equal to the sum of the two **micro-constants** for the component reactions.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Thus, in this example there are four micro-constants whose values are subject to two constraints; in consequence, only the two macro-constant values, for K1 and K2 can be derived from experimental data.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Micro-constant values can, in principle, be determined using a spectroscopic technique, such as infrared spectroscopy, where each micro-species gives a different signal.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Although the value of a micro-constant cannot be determined from experimental data, site occupancy, which is proportional to the micro-constant value, can be very important for biological activity.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Therefore, various methods have been developed for estimating micro-constant values.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] For example, the isomerization constant for L-DOPA has been estimated to have a value of 0.9, so the micro-species L1H and L2H have almost equal concentrations at all pH values.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] In the approximation of ideal behaviour, activity is replaced by concentration. pH is measured by means of a glass electrode, a mixed equilibrium constant, also known as a Brønsted constant, may result.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] It all depends on whether the electrode is calibrated by reference to solutions of known activity or known concentration.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] In the latter case the equilibrium constant would be a concentration quotient.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] If the electrode is calibrated in terms of known hydrogen ion concentrations it would be better to write p[H] rather than pH, but this suggestion is not generally adopted.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Hydrolysis constants are usually reported in the *β** form and therefore often have values much less than 1.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Conditional constants, also known as apparent constants, are concentration quotients which are not true equilibrium constants but can be derived from them.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] A very common instance is where pH is fixed at a particular value.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] This conditional constant will vary with pH.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] That is the pH where the ligand sequesters the metal most effectively.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] In biochemistry equilibrium constants are often measured at a pH fixed by means of a buffer solution.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Such constants are, by definition, conditional and different values may be obtained when using different buffers.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] For equilibria in a gas phase, fugacity, *f*, is used in place of activity.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] However, fugacity has the dimension of pressure, so it must be divided by a standard pressure, usually 1 bar, in order to produce a dimensionless quantity, ⁠*f*/*p*o⁠.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] An equilibrium constant is expressed in terms of the dimensionless quantity.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Fugacity is related to partial pressure, *$p_{X}$*, by a dimensionless fugacity coefficient *ϕ*: *$f_{X}=\phi _{X}p_{X}$*.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Usually the standard pressure is omitted from such expressions.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Expressions for equilibrium constants in the gas phase then resemble the expression for solution equilibria with fugacity coefficient in place of activity coefficient and partial pressure in place of concentration.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Thermodynamic equilibrium is characterized by the free energy for the whole (closed) system being a minimum.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] For systems at constant temperature and pressure the Gibbs free energy is minimum.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The slope of the reaction free energy with respect to the extent of reaction, *ξ*, is zero when the free energy is at its minimum value.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The free energy change, d*G*r, can be expressed as a weighted sum of change in amount times the chemical potential, the partial molar free energy of the species.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] where *nj* are the stoichiometric coefficients of the reactants in the equilibrium equation, and *mj* are the coefficients of the products.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The chemical potential, *μi*, of the *i*th species can be calculated in terms of its activity, *ai*.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] This relates the standard Gibbs free energy change, Δ*G*o to an equilibrium constant, *K*, the reaction quotient of activity values at equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] At equilibrium the rate of the forward reaction is equal to the backward reaction rate.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] According to Guldberg and Waage, equilibrium is attained when the forward and backward reaction rates are equal to each other.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] This particular concentration quotient, $K^{c}$ , has the dimension of concentration, but the thermodynamic equilibrium constant, K, is always dimensionless.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] It is very rare for activity coefficient values to have been determined experimentally for a system at equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] There are three options for dealing with the situation where activity coefficient values are not known from experimental measurements.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Assume that the activity coefficients are all equal to 1.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] This is acceptable when all concentrations are very low.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] For equilibria in solution use a medium of high ionic strength.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] In effect this redefines the standard state as referring to the medium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Activity coefficients in the standard state are, by definition, equal to 1.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The value of an equilibrium constant determined in this manner is dependent on the ionic strength.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] When published constants refer to an ionic strength other than the one required for a particular application, they may be adjusted by means of specific ion theory (SIT) and other theories.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Therefore, *K*, must be a dimensionless number from which a logarithm can be derived.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Now, each activity term can be expressed as a product of a concentration $[X]$ and a corresponding activity coefficient, $\gamma (X)$ .
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The assumption underlying this practice is that the quotient of activities is constant under the conditions in which the equilibrium constant value is determined.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] These conditions are usually achieved by keeping the reaction temperature constant and by using a medium of relatively high ionic strength as the solvent.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] It is not unusual, particularly in texts relating to biochemical equilibria, to see an equilibrium constant value quoted with a dimension.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The justification for this practice is that the concentration scale used may be either mol dm−3 or mmol dm−3, so that the concentration unit has to be stated in order to avoid there being any ambiguity.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The apparent dimension of this *K* value is concentration1−p−q; this may be written as M(1−p−q) or mM(1−p−q), where the symbol M signifies a molar concentration (1M = 1 mol dm−3).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The apparent dimension of a dissociation constant is the reciprocal of the apparent dimension of the corresponding association constant, and *vice versa*.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] When discussing the thermodynamics of chemical equilibria it is necessary to take dimensionality into account.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Replace each concentration term $[X]$ by the dimensionless quotient ${\frac {[X]}{[X^{0}]}}$ , where $[X^{0}]$ is the concentration of reagent X in its standard state (usually 1 mol/L or 1 bar).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] By definition the numerical value of $\gamma (X^{0})$ is 1, so Γ also has a numerical value of 1.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] In both approaches the numerical value of the stability constant is unchanged.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The first is more useful for practical purposes; in fact, the unit of the concentration quotient is often attached to a published stability constant value in the biochemical literature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The second approach is consistent with the standard exposition of Debye–Hückel theory, where $\gamma (AB)$ , *etc*. are taken to be pure numbers.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] the concentration of water may be taken as being constant and the formation of the hydronium ion is implicit.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Water concentration is omitted from expressions defining equilibrium constants, except when solutions are very concentrated.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Similar considerations apply to metal ion hydrolysis reactions.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] If both the equilibrium constant, K and the standard enthalpy change, $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ , for a reaction have been determined experimentally, the standard entropy change for the reaction is easily derived.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] To a first approximation the standard enthalpy change is independent of temperature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] This equation can be used to calculate the value of log K at a temperature, T2, knowing the value at temperature T1.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The van 't Hoff equation also shows that, for an exothermic reaction ( $\Delta H<0$ ), when temperature increases *K* decreases and when temperature decreases *K* increases, in accordance with Le Chatelier's principle.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The reverse applies when the reaction is endothermic.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] When *K* has been determined at more than two temperatures, a straight line fitting procedure may be applied to a plot of $\ln K$ against $1/T$ to obtain a value for $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ .
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Error propagation theory can be used to show that, with this procedure, the error on the calculated $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ value is much greater than the error on individual log K values.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Consequently, K needs to be determined to high precision when using this method.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] For example, with a silver ion-selective electrode each log K value was determined with a precision of ca.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] 0.001 and the method was applied successfully.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Standard thermodynamic arguments can be used to show that, more generally, enthalpy will change with temperature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] where *C**p* is the heat capacity at constant pressure.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The calculation of *K* at a particular temperature from a known *K* at another given temperature can be approached as follows if standard thermodynamic properties are available.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] where Δr*G*o is the reaction standard Gibbs energy, which is the sum of the standard Gibbs energies of the reaction products minus the sum of standard Gibbs energies of reactants.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Here, the term "standard" denotes the ideal behaviour (i.e., an infinite dilution) and a hypothetical standard concentration (typically 1 mol/kg).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] It does not imply any particular temperature or pressure because, although contrary to IUPAC recommendation, it is more convenient when describing aqueous systems over wide temperature and pressure ranges.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] In the above equation, the effect of temperature on Gibbs energy (and thus on the equilibrium constant) is ascribed entirely to heat capacity.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] To evaluate the integrals in this equation, the form of the dependence of heat capacity on temperature needs to be known.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] If the standard molar heat capacity *C*o *p* can be approximated by some analytic function of temperature (e.g. the Shomate equation), then the integrals involved in calculating other parameters may be solved to yield analytic expressions for them.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The constants *A*, *B*, *C*, *a*, *b* and the absolute entropy, *S̆* o 298 K, required for evaluation of *C*o *p*(*T*), as well as the values of *G*298 K and *S*298 K for many species are tabulated in the literature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The pressure dependence of the equilibrium constant is usually weak in the range of pressures normally encountered in industry, and therefore, it is usually neglected in practice.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] This is true for condensed reactant/products (i.e., when reactants and products are solids or liquid) as well as gaseous ones.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] If the pressure is increased by the addition of an inert gas, then neither the composition at equilibrium nor the equilibrium constant are appreciably affected (because the partial pressures remain constant, assuming an ideal-gas behaviour of all gases involved).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] In the example reaction above, the number of moles changes from 4 to 2, and an increase of pressure by system compression will result in appreciably more ammonia in the equilibrium mixture.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] where *p* denote the partial pressures and *X* the mole fractions of the components, *P* is the total system pressure, *Kp* is the equilibrium constant expressed in terms of partial pressures and *KX* is the equilibrium constant expressed in terms of mole fractions.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The above change in composition is in accordance with Le Chatelier's principle and does not involve any change of the equilibrium constant with the total system pressure.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Indeed, for ideal-gas reactions *Kp* is independent of pressure.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] In a condensed phase, the pressure dependence of the equilibrium constant is associated with the reaction volume.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] where *V̄* denotes a partial molar volume of a reactant or a product.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The matter is complicated as partial molar volume is itself dependent on pressure.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Isotopic substitution can lead to changes in the values of equilibrium constants, especially if hydrogen is replaced by deuterium (or tritium).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] This *equilibrium isotope effect* is analogous to the kinetic isotope effect on rate constants, and is primarily due to the change in zero-point vibrational energy of H–X bonds due to the change in mass upon isotopic substitution.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The zero-point energy is inversely proportional to the square root of the mass of the vibrating hydrogen atom, and will therefore be smaller for a D–X bond that for an H–X bond.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] An example is a hydrogen atom abstraction reaction R' + H–R ⇌ R'–H + R with equilibrium constant KH, where R' and R are organic radicals such that R' forms a stronger bond to hydrogen than does R.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The decrease in zero-point energy due to deuterium substitution will then be more important for R'–H than for R–H, and R'–D will be stabilized more than R–D, so that the equilibrium constant KD for R' + D–R ⇌ R'–D + R is greater than KH.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] This is summarized in the rule *the heavier atom favors the stronger bond*.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] Similar effects occur in solution for acid dissociation constants (Ka) which describe the transfer of H+ or D+ from a weak aqueous acid to a solvent molecule: HA + H2O = H3O+ + A− or DA + D2O ⇌ D3O+ + A−.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The deuterated acid is studied in heavy water, since if it were dissolved in ordinary water the deuterium would rapidly exchange with hydrogen in the solvent.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The product species H3O+ (or D3O+) is a stronger acid than the solute acid, so that it dissociates more easily, and its H–O (or D–O) bond is weaker than the H–A (or D–A) bond of the solute acid.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] The decrease in zero-point energy due to isotopic substitution is therefore less important in D3O+ than in DA so that KD < KH, and the deuterated acid in D2O is weaker than the non-deuterated acid in H2O.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] In many cases the difference of logarithmic constants pKD – pKH is about 0.6, so that the pD corresponding to 50% dissociation of the deuterated acid is about 0.6 units higher than the pH for 50% dissociation of the non-deuterated acid.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/equilibrium-constant] For similar reasons the self-ionization of heavy water is less than that of ordinary water at the same temperature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] In chemistry, **Le Chatelier's principle** (pronounced UK: /lə ʃæˈtɛljeɪ/ or US: /ˈʃɑːtəljeɪ/) is a principle used to predict the effect of a change in conditions on chemical equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Other names include **Chatelier's principle**, **Braun–Le Chatelier principle, Le Chatelier–Braun principle** or the **equilibrium law**.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] In scenarios outside thermodynamic equilibrium, there can arise phenomena in contradiction to an over-general statement of Le Chatelier's principle.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Le Chatelier's principle is sometimes alluded to in discussions of topics other than thermodynamics.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The response illustrates 'moderation' in ways evident in two related thermodynamic equilibria.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] To give this scenario physical meaning, the 'driving' variable and the 'moderating' variable must be subject to separate independent experimental controls and measurements.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The principle can be stated in two ways which are formally different but substantially equivalent, and, in a sense, mutually 'reciprocal'.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The two ways illustrate the Maxwell relations, and the stability of thermodynamic equilibrium according to the second law of thermodynamics, evident as the spread of energy amongst the state variables of the system in response to an imposed change.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The two ways of statement differ in their experimental protocols.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] They share an *index protocol* (denoted ${\mathcal {P}}_{\mathrm {i} }),$ which may be described as 'changed driver, moderation permitted'.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The two ways of statement differ in their respective *compared protocols*.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] This way compares ${\mathcal {P}}_{\mathrm {i} }$ with ${\mathcal {P}}_{\mathrm {n} },$ to compare the effects of the imposed the change $\Delta L$ with and without moderation.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] This way also uses two experimental protocols, ${\mathcal {P}}_{\mathrm {i} }$ and ${\mathcal {P}}_{\mathrm {f} }$ , to compare the index effect $\delta _{\mathrm {i} }M$ with the effect $\delta _{\mathrm {f} }M$ of 'moderation' alone.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The *index protocol* ${\mathcal {P}}_{\mathrm {i} }$ is executed first; the response of prime interest, $\delta _{\mathrm {i} }M,$ is observed, and the response $\Delta X$ of the 'moderating' variable is also measured.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The duration of adjustment depends on the strength of the negative feedback to the initial shock.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] While well rooted in chemical equilibrium, Le Chatelier's principle can also be used in describing mechanical systems, in that a system put under stress will respond in such a way as to reduce or minimize that stress.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Moreover, the response will generally be enacted through the mechanism that most easily relieves that stress.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Shear pins and other such sacrificial devices are design elements that protect systems against stress applied in undesired manners to relieve it so as to prevent more extensive damage to the entire system, a practical engineering application of Le Chatelier's principle.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Changing the concentration of a chemical will shift the equilibrium to the side (reactants or products) that would counter that change in concentration.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The chemical system will attempt to partly oppose the change that affected the original state of equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] In turn, the rate of reaction, extent, and yield of products will be altered corresponding to the impact on the system.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Suppose we were to increase the concentration of CO in the system.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Using Le Chatelier's principle, we can predict that the concentration of methanol will increase, decreasing the total change in CO.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] If we are to add a chemical species to the overall reaction, the reaction will favor the side opposing the addition of the species.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Likewise, the subtraction of a species would cause the reaction to "fill the gap" and favor the side where the species was reduced.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] This observation is supported by the collision theory.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] As the concentration of CO is increased, the frequency of successful collisions of that reactant would increase also, allowing for an increase in forward reaction, and generation of the product.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Even if the desired product is not thermodynamically favored, the end-product can be obtained if it is continuously removed from the solution.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The effect of a change in concentration is often exploited synthetically for condensation reactions (i.e., reactions that extrude water) that are equilibrium processes (such as the formation of an ester from carboxylic acid and alcohol, or the formation of an imine from an amine and aldehyde).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] This can be achieved by physically sequestering water, by adding desiccants like anhydrous magnesium sulfate or molecular sieves, or by continuous removal of water by distillation, often facilitated by a Dean-Stark apparatus.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The effect of changing the temperature in the equilibrium can be made clear by 1) incorporating heat as either a reactant or a product, and 2) assuming that an increase in temperature increases the heat content of a system.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] When the reaction is exothermic (Δ*H* is negative and energy is released), heat is included as a product, and when the reaction is endothermic (Δ*H* is positive and energy is consumed), heat is included as a reactant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Hence, whether increasing or decreasing the temperature would favor the forward or the reverse reaction can be determined by applying the same principle as with concentration changes.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] If the temperature were increased, the heat content of the system would increase, so the system would consume some of that heat by shifting the equilibrium to the left, thereby producing less ammonia.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] In exothermic reactions, an increase in temperature decreases the equilibrium constant *K*, whereas in endothermic reactions, an increase in temperature increases *K*.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Le Chatelier's principle applied to changes in concentration or pressure can be understood by giving *K* a constant value.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The effect of temperature on equilibria, however, involves a change in the equilibrium constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The dependence of *K* on temperature is determined by the sign of Δ*H*.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The theoretical basis of this dependence is given by the Van 't Hoff equation.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The equilibrium concentrations of the products and reactants do not directly depend on the total pressure of the system.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] They may depend on the partial pressure of the products and reactants, but if the number of moles of gaseous reactants is equal to the number of moles of gaseous products, pressure has no effect on equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Changing total pressure by adding an inert gas at constant volume does not affect the equilibrium concentrations (see § Effect of adding an inert gas).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Changing total pressure by changing the volume of the system changes the partial pressures of the products and reactants and can affect the equilibrium concentrations (see § Effect of change in volume below).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Changing the volume of the system changes the partial pressures of the products and reactants and can affect the equilibrium concentrations.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] With a pressure increase due to a decrease in volume, the side of the equilibrium with fewer moles is more favorable, whereas with a pressure decrease due to an increase in volume, the side with more moles is more favorable.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] There is no effect on a reaction where the number of moles of gas is the same on each side of the chemical equation.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Note the number of moles of gas on the left-hand side and the number of moles of gas on the right-hand side.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] When the volume of the system is changed, the partial pressures of the gases change.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] If we were to decrease pressure by increasing volume, the equilibrium of the above reaction would shift to the left, because the reactant side has a greater number of moles than the product side does.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The system tries to counteract the decrease in partial pressure of gas molecules by shifting to the side that exerts greater pressure.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Similarly, if we were to increase pressure by decreasing volume, the equilibrium shifts to the right, counteracting the pressure increase by shifting to the side with fewer moles of gas that exert less pressure.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] If the volume is increased because there are more moles of gas on the reactant side, this change is more significant in the denominator of the equilibrium constant expression, causing a shift in equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] An inert gas (or noble gas), such as helium, is one that does not react with other elements or compounds.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Adding an inert gas into a gas-phase equilibrium at constant volume does not result in a shift.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] This is because the addition of a non-reactive gas does not change the equilibrium equation, as the inert gas appears on both sides of the chemical reaction equation.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] For example, if A and B react to form C and D, but X does not participate in the reaction: ${\ce {{\mathit {a}}A{}+{\mathit {b}}B{}+{\mathit {x}}X<=>{\mathit {c}}C{}+{\mathit {d}}D{}+{\mathit {x}}X}}$ .
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] While it is true that the total pressure of the system increases, the total pressure does not have any effect on the equilibrium constant; rather, it is a change in partial pressures that will cause a shift in the equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] If, however, the volume is allowed to increase in the process, the partial pressures of all gases would be decreased resulting in a shift towards the side with the greater number of moles of gas.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The shift will never occur on the side with fewer moles of gas.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] It is also known as Le Chatelier's postulate.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] A catalyst increases the rate of a reaction without being consumed in the reaction.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The use of a catalyst does not affect the position and composition of the equilibrium of a reaction, because both the forward and backward reactions are sped up by the same factor.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] In the above reaction, iron (Fe) and molybdenum (Mo) will function as catalysts if present.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] They will accelerate any reactions, but they do not affect the state of the equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Le Chatelier's principle refers to states of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The latter are stable against perturbations that satisfy certain criteria; this is essential to the definition of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] It states that changes in the temperature, pressure, volume, or concentration of a system will result in predictable and opposing changes in the system in order to achieve a new equilibrium state.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] A simple body or a complex thermodynamic system can also be in a stationary state with non-zero rates of flow and chemical reaction; sometimes the word "equilibrium" is used in reference to such a state, though by definition it is not a thermodynamic equilibrium state.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Sometimes, it is proposed to consider Le Chatelier's principle for such states.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] For this exercise, rates of flow and of chemical reaction must be considered.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Such rates are not supplied by equilibrium thermodynamics.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] For such states, there are no simple statements that echo Le Chatelier's principle.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Prigogine and Defay demonstrate that such a scenario may exhibit moderation, or may exhibit a measured amount of anti-moderation, though not a run-away anti-moderation that goes to completion.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The example analysed by Prigogine and Defay is the Haber process.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] This situation is clarified by considering two basic methods of analysis of a process.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] One is the classical approach of Gibbs, the other uses the near- or local equilibrium approach of De Donder.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The Gibbs approach requires thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The Gibbs approach is reliable within its proper scope, thermodynamic equilibrium, though of course it does not cover non-equilibrium scenarios.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The De Donder approach can cover equilibrium scenarios, but also covers non-equilibrium scenarios in which there is only local thermodynamic equilibrium, and not thermodynamic equilibrium proper.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The De Donder approach allows state variables called extents of reaction to be independent variables, though in the Gibbs approach, such variables are not independent.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Thermodynamic non-equilibrium scenarios can contradict an over-general statement of Le Chatelier's Principle.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] The concept of systemic maintenance of a stable steady state despite perturbations has a variety of names, and has been studied in a variety of contexts, chiefly in the natural sciences.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] In chemistry, the principle is used to manipulate the outcomes of reversible reactions, often to increase their yield.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] In pharmacology, the binding of ligands to receptors may shift the equilibrium according to Le Chatelier's principle, thereby explaining the diverse phenomena of receptor activation and desensitization.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] In biology, the concept of homeostasis is different from Le Chatelier's principle, in that homoeostasis is generally maintained by processes of active character, as distinct from the passive or dissipative character of the processes described by Le Chatelier's principle in thermodynamics.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] In economics, even further from thermodynamics, allusion to the principle is sometimes regarded as helping explain the price equilibrium of efficient economic systems.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] In some dynamic systems, the end-state cannot be determined from the shock or perturbation.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] In economics, a similar concept also named after Le Chatelier was introduced by American economist Paul Samuelson in 1947.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] There the generalized Le Chatelier principle is for a maximum condition of economic equilibrium: Where all unknowns of a function are independently variable, auxiliary constraints—"just-binding" in leaving initial equilibrium unchanged—reduce the response to a parameter change.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Thus, factor-demand and commodity-supply elasticities are hypothesized to be lower in the short run than in the long run because of the fixed-cost constraint in the short run.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/le-chatelier-s-principle] Since the change of the value of an objective function in a neighbourhood of the maximum position is described by the envelope theorem, Le Chatelier's principle can be shown to be a corollary thereof.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] Mathematically, it is defined as the ratio of the activities (or molar concentrations) of the product species over those of the reactant species involved in the chemical reaction, taking stoichiometric coefficients of the reaction into account as exponents of the concentrations.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] In equilibrium, the reaction quotient is constant over time and is equal to the equilibrium constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] The reaction is written as an equilibrium even though, in many cases, it may appear that all of the reactants on one side have been converted to the other side.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] where $\{\mathrm {X} \}_{t}$ denotes the *instantaneous* activity of a species $\mathrm {X}$ at time t .
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] where $\textstyle \prod _{j}$ denotes the product across all j -indexed variables, $a_{j}(t)$ is the activity of species j at time t , and $\nu _{j}$ is the stoichiometric number (the stoichiometric coefficient multiplied by +1 for products and −1 for starting materials).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] As the reaction proceeds with the passage of time, the species' activities, and hence the reaction quotient, change in a way that reduces the free energy of the chemical system.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] where *K* is a constant independent of initial composition, known as the equilibrium constant.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] The reaction proceeds in the forward direction (towards larger values of $Q_{\mathrm {r} }$ ) when $\Delta _{\mathrm {r} }G<0$ or in the reverse direction (towards smaller values of $Q_{r}$ ) when $\Delta _{\mathrm {r} }G>0$ .
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] Eventually, as the reaction mixture reaches chemical equilibrium, the activities of the components (and thus the reaction quotient) approach constant values.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] The timescale of this process depends on the rate constants of the forward and reverse reactions.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] In principle, equilibrium is approached asymptotically at $t\to \infty$ ; in practice, equilibrium is considered to be reached, in a practical sense, when concentrations of the equilibrating species no longer change perceptibly with respect to the analytical instruments and methods used.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] This quantity, $\Delta _{\mathrm {r} }G^{\circ }$ , is called the *standard Gibbs free energy of reaction*.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] All reactions, regardless of how favorable, are equilibrium processes, though practically speaking, if no starting material is detected after a certain point by a particular analytical technique in question, the reaction is said to go to completion.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] In biochemistry, the reaction quotient is often referred to as the mass-action ratio with the symbol $\Gamma$ .
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] The reaction quotient can be used to predict the direction and extent of an equilibrium chemical reaction.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] At equilibrium, the reaction quotient ( Q ) is equal to the equilibrium constant ( K ) for the reaction, where $Q=K$ .
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] If $Q>K$ , the formation of reactants is favored.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] This is because the ratio of the numerator to the denominator in Q is greater than that of K , indicating there are more products than at equilibrium.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] As Le Chatelier's Principle states systems tend towards equilibrium, the equilibrium shifts in the reverse direction favoring the formation of the products.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/reaction-quotient] Similarly, when $Q<K$ , the formation of products is favored and the reaction is progressing in the forwards direction.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] A solubility equilibrium exists when a chemical compound in the solid state is in chemical equilibrium with a solution containing the compound.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] This type of equilibrium is an example of dynamic equilibrium in that some individual molecules migrate between the solid and solution phases such that the rates of dissolution and precipitation are equal to one another.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] When equilibrium is established and the solid has not all dissolved, the solution is said to be saturated.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The concentration of the solute in a saturated solution is known as the solubility.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Units of solubility may be molar (mol dm−3) or expressed as mass per unit volume, such as μg mL−1.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] A solution containing a higher concentration of solute than the solubility is said to be supersaturated.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] A supersaturated solution may be induced to come to equilibrium by the addition of a "seed" which may be a tiny crystal of the solute, or a tiny solid particle, which initiates precipitation.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] There are three main types of solubility equilibria.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The equilibrium constant is known in this case as a solubility product.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] This is characteristic of the dissolution of weak acids or weak bases in aqueous media of varying pH.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] In each case an equilibrium constant can be specified as a quotient of activities.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] This equilibrium constant is dimensionless as activity is a dimensionless quantity.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] However, use of activities is very inconvenient, so the equilibrium constant is usually divided by the quotient of activity coefficients, to become a quotient of concentrations.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] See Equilibrium chemistry § Equilibrium constant for details.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Moreover, the activity of a solid is, by definition, equal to 1 so it is omitted from the defining expression.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] A solubility product has a similar functionality to an equilibrium constant though formally *K*sp has the dimension of (concentration)*p*+*q*.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Solubility is sensitive to changes in temperature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] For example, sugar is more soluble in hot water than cool water.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] It occurs because solubility products, like other types of equilibrium constants, are functions of temperature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] In accordance with Le Chatelier's Principle, when the dissolution process is endothermic (heat is absorbed), solubility increases with rising temperature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] This effect is the basis for the process of recrystallization, which can be used to purify a chemical compound.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] When dissolution is exothermic (heat is released) solubility decreases with rising temperature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Sodium sulfate shows increasing solubility with temperature below about 32.4 °C, but a decreasing solubility at higher temperature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] This is because the solid phase is the decahydrate (Na 2SO 4·10H 2O) below the transition temperature, but a different hydrate above that temperature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The common-ion effect is the effect of decreased solubility of one salt when another salt that has an ion in common with it is also present.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The concentrations [Ag+] and [Cl−] are equal because one mole of AgCl would dissociate into one mole of Ag+ and one mole of Cl−.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Let the concentration of [Ag+(aq)] be denoted by *x*.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Now suppose that sodium chloride is also present, at a concentration of 0.01 mol dm−3 = 0.01 M.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] In gravimetric analysis for silver, the reduction in solubility due to the common ion effect is used to ensure "complete" precipitation of AgCl.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The thermodynamic solubility constant is defined for large monocrystals.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Solubility will increase with decreasing size of solute particle (or droplet) because of the additional surface energy.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] This effect is generally small unless particles become very small, typically smaller than 1 μm.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Equilibria are defined for specific crystal phases.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Therefore, the solubility product is expected to be different depending on the phase of the solid.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] For example, aragonite and calcite will have different solubility products even though they have both the same chemical identity (calcium carbonate).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Under any given conditions one phase will be thermodynamically more stable than the other; therefore, this phase will form when thermodynamic equilibrium is established.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] However, kinetic factors may favor the formation the unfavorable precipitate (e.g. aragonite), which is then said to be in a metastable state.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] In pharmacology, the metastable state is sometimes referred to as amorphous state.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Amorphous drugs have higher solubility than their crystalline counterparts due to the absence of long-distance interactions inherent in crystal lattice.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Thus, it takes less energy to solvate the molecules in amorphous phase.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The effect of amorphous phase on solubility is widely used to make drugs more soluble.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] For condensed phases (solids and liquids), the pressure dependence of solubility is typically weak and usually neglected in practice.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The pressure dependence of solubility does occasionally have practical significance.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] For example, precipitation fouling of oil fields and wells by calcium sulfate (which decreases its solubility with decreasing pressure) can result in decreased productivity with time.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Dissolution of an **organic solid** can be described as an equilibrium between the substance in its solid and dissolved forms.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The activity of a pure solid is, by definition, unity.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Therefore $K^{\ominus }=\left\{\mathrm {{C}_{12}{H}_{22}{O}_{11}(aq)} \right\}$ The activity of a substance, A, in solution can be expressed as the product of the concentration, [A], and an activity coefficient, *γ*.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] This is equivalent to defining the standard state as the saturated solution so that the activity coefficient is equal to one.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The solubility constant is a true constant only if the activity coefficient is not affected by the presence of any other solutes that may be present.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The unit of the solubility constant is the same as the unit of the concentration of the solute.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] This shows that the solubility of sucrose at 25 °C is nearly 2 mol dm−3 (540 g/L).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Sucrose is unusual in that it does not easily form a supersaturated solution at higher concentrations, as do most other carbohydrates.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] When the solubility of the salt is very low the activity coefficients of the ions in solution are nearly equal to one.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Solubility products are often expressed in logarithmic form.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The smaller the value of *K*sp, or the more negative the log value, the lower the solubility.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Some salts are not fully dissociated in solution.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Examples include MgSO4, famously discovered by Manfred Eigen to be present in seawater as both an inner sphere complex and an outer sphere complex.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The solubility of such salts is calculated by the method outlined in dissolution with reaction.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] For hydroxides, solubility products are often given in a modified form, *K**sp, using hydrogen ion concentration in place of hydroxide ion concentration.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] A typical reaction with dissolution involves a weak base, B, dissolving in an acidic aqueous solution. $\mathrm {B} \mathrm {(s)} +\mathrm {H} ^{+}\mathrm {(aq)} \leftrightharpoons \mathrm {BH} ^{+}(\mathrm {aq)}$ This reaction is very important for pharmaceutical products.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Dissolution of weak acids in alkaline media is similarly important. $\mathrm {HA(s)+OH^{-}(aq)\leftrightharpoons A^{-}(aq)+H_{2}O}$ The uncharged molecule usually has lower solubility than the ionic form, so solubility depends on pH and the acid dissociation constant of the solute.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The term "intrinsic solubility" is used to describe the solubility of the un-ionized form in the absence of acid or alkali.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Leaching of aluminium salts from rocks and soil by acid rain is another example of dissolution with reaction: alumino-silicates are bases which react with the acid to form soluble species, such as Al3+(aq).
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Formation of a chemical complex may also change solubility.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The addition of water softeners to washing powders to inhibit the formation of soap scum provides an example of practical importance.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The determination of solubility is fraught with difficulties.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] First and foremost is the difficulty in establishing that the system is in equilibrium at the chosen temperature.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] This is because both precipitation and dissolution reactions may be extremely slow.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] If the process is very slow solvent evaporation may be an issue.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] With very insoluble substances, the concentrations in solution are very low and difficult to determine.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The methods used fall broadly into two categories, static and dynamic.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] In static methods a mixture is brought to equilibrium and the concentration of a species in the solution phase is determined by chemical analysis.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] This usually requires separation of the solid and solution phases.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] In order to do this the equilibration and separation should be performed in a thermostatted room.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Very low concentrations can be measured if a radioactive tracer is incorporated in the solid phase.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] A variation of the static method is to add a solution of the substance in a non-aqueous solvent, such as dimethyl sulfoxide, to an aqueous buffer mixture.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Immediate precipitation may occur giving a cloudy mixture.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The solubility measured for such a mixture is known as "kinetic solubility".
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The cloudiness is due to the fact that the precipitate particles are very small resulting in Tyndall scattering.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] In fact the particles are so small that the particle size effect comes into play and kinetic solubility is often greater than equilibrium solubility.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Over time the cloudiness will disappear as the size of the crystallites increases, and eventually equilibrium will be reached in a process known as precipitate ageing.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Solubility values of organic acids, bases, and ampholytes of pharmaceutical interest may be obtained by a process called "Chasing equilibrium solubility".
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] In this procedure, a quantity of substance is first dissolved at a pH where it exists predominantly in its ionized form and then a precipitate of the neutral (un-ionized) species is formed by changing the pH.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] Subsequently, the rate of change of pH due to precipitation or dissolution is monitored and strong acid and base titrant are added to adjust the pH to discover the equilibrium conditions when the two rates are equal.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] The advantage of this method is that it is relatively fast as the quantity of precipitate formed is quite small.
[src:chemical-equilibrium/solubility-equilibrium] However, the performance of the method may be affected by the formation supersaturated solutions.
